interactiveObj = {"$ambrosia":"aero:interactive:9417ac60-5f60-11ea-8e69-affb2224d7e8:*","$id":"0a70c880-44e0-11ed-8033-99dcb6d05300","$workspaceId":"7fff47c0-44d6-11ed-bcef-d5307f42495c","$projectId":"86cb0040-44df-11ed-8442-dbcbc27803ca","annotations":[],"configSchemaVersion":"/pluginGenericSchema/v1","config":{"stage":{"sections":[{"rowsAreFullWidth":false,"backgroundImageUrl":"","rows":[{"columns":[{"stageElements":[{"type":"stage-element-text","value":{"object":"value","document":{"object":"document","data":{},"nodes":[{"object":"block","type":"heading-two","ref":"08ec8fa1-33bd-435d-a60c-5e243b98cfc0","nodes":[{"object":"text","text":"Dividend Smoothing","marks":[]}],"data":{}}]}},"config":{"cssClass":""},"ref":"6aec93d9-ca5f-4889-80c6-58c03b93eac4"}]}]},{"columns":[{"stageElements":[{"type":"stage-element-text","value":{"object":"value","document":{"object":"document","data":{},"nodes":[{"object":"block","type":"paragraph","ref":"9c0dea0b-4ba5-43d1-856c-f8f2ea32ee05","nodes":[{"object":"text","text":"Firms can change dividends at any time, but in practice they vary the sizes of their dividends relatively infrequently. For example, General Motors (GM) changed the amount of its regular dividend only eight times over a 20-year period. Yet during that same period, GM’s earnings varied widely, as shown in ","marks":[]},{"object":"inline","type":"reference-link","ref":"a50da631-3018-4e9a-b151-6532e2dc9b5c","nodes":[{"object":"text","text":"Figure 17.7","marks":[]}],"data":{"reference":"85765ad0-44e1-11ed-8442-dbcbc27803ca"}},{"object":"text","text":".","marks":[]}],"data":{}}]}},"config":{"cssClass":""},"ref":"02ca59fa-f2f9-45a9-b822-e199725eda35"}]}]},{"columns":[{"stageElements":[{"type":"stage-element-image","config":{"url":{"$ambrosia":"aero:asset:upload","urn":"urn:aero:cb03cb60-44e0-11ed-9967-59bbd5f34c83","asset":{"urn":"urn:aero:cb03cb60-44e0-11ed-9967-59bbd5f34c83","asset":{"assetProvider":"ALFRESCO","id":"cb03cb60-44e0-11ed-9967-59bbd5f34c83","assetMediaType":"image","assetVisibility":"GLOBAL","ownerId":"e88133a0-8dc4-11eb-964e-4d7e264c9958","subscriptionId":"f0afd4d0-d2ff-11ea-9998-d57e1e28aca1","alfrescoId":"a3933c8e-166f-417c-957f-1f7a35673431","name":"FG_17_007.jpg","version":"2.0","lastModifiedDate":1664998397,"lastSyncDate":1665085928},"source":{"small":{"width":468,"url":"https://assets-bronte-qaint.pearson.com/cb03cb60-44e0-11ed-9967-59bbd5f34c83/small/4d702a036b1b5046ce4f56c8786cdc0c.jpeg","height":300},"original":{"width":937,"url":"https://assets-bronte-qaint.pearson.com/cb03cb60-44e0-11ed-9967-59bbd5f34c83/medium/4d702a036b1b5046ce4f56c8786cdc0c.jpeg","height":600},"medium":{"width":937,"url":"https://assets-bronte-qaint.pearson.com/cb03cb60-44e0-11ed-9967-59bbd5f34c83/medium/4d702a036b1b5046ce4f56c8786cdc0c.jpeg","height":600},"thumb":{"width":234,"url":"https://assets-bronte-qaint.pearson.com/cb03cb60-44e0-11ed-9967-59bbd5f34c83/thumb/4d702a036b1b5046ce4f56c8786cdc0c.jpeg","height":150}},"metadata":{"altText":"","workURN":"","caption":"<p>Compared to GM&#x2019;s earnings, its dividend payments were relatively stable until it finally suspended them in 2008 prior to filing for bankruptcy the next year. (Data adjusted for splits, earnings exclude extraordinary items.)</p>","alfrescoPath":"bronte-e2e-testing-qaint/documentLibrary/BV E2E Test/[10-05-2022] Berk","originalAssetName":"FG_17_007.jpg","longDesc":"","height":"513"}}},"alt":"","caption":"<p>Compared to GM&#x2019;s earnings, its dividend payments were relatively stable until it finally suspended them in 2008 prior to filing for bankruptcy the next year. (Data adjusted for splits, earnings exclude extraordinary items.)</p>","layout":{"captionPosition":"Below"},"credit":"<p><em>Source</em>&#x200A;: Compustat and Capital IQ.</p>","activityLabel":"Figure 17.7","activityTitle":"GM&#x2019;s Earnings and Dividends per Share, 1985&#x2013;2008"},"height":513,"ref":"ce64222c-234d-437a-a985-3435bd6735af"}]}]},{"columns":[{"stageElements":[{"type":"stage-element-text","value":{"object":"value","document":{"object":"document","data":{},"nodes":[{"object":"block","type":"paragraph","ref":"3feb8e03-f42a-4e5b-9fa3-60521c0ed4c9","nodes":[{"object":"text","text":"The pattern seen with GM is typical of most firms that pay dividends. Firms adjust dividends relatively infrequently, and dividends are much less volatile than earnings. This practice of maintaining relatively constant dividends is called ","marks":[]},{"data":{"ref":"dec462c9-8c62-4576-b04d-fa95b207d950","stage":{"ref":"eb90e7de-0e6d-4b9b-aa10-9234dd77a65a","sections":[{"ref":"1e0b5700-a0f9-4cc9-b5ae-cecc2ce12d29","rows":[{"ref":"eeb0bfc7-afd9-4941-9a58-ba6b7b83358b","columns":[{"ref":"64bd803c-2298-4d72-a3d0-e4dafc74a080","stageElements":[{"ref":"a1925f71-76c5-45ed-9e35-c8a859043612","type":"stage-element-text","value":{"object":"value","document":{"object":"document","data":{},"nodes":[{"object":"block","type":"button","ref":"ad173afb-2567-4f48-a45d-2db968f04b06","nodes":[{"object":"block","type":"paragraph","ref":"146f3fcb-2e0e-4ef6-baae-7f6a9bc35601","nodes":[{"object":"text","text":"The practice of maintaining relatively constant dividends.","marks":[]}],"data":{}}],"data":{}}]}}}]}]}]}]}},"nodes":[{"object":"text","text":"dividend smoothing","marks":[]}],"object":"inline","type":"key-term","ref":"42ebc9eb-b01d-4894-b0c6-5a26b9782926"},{"object":"text","text":". Firms also increase dividends much more frequently than they cut them. For example, from 1971 to 2001, only 5.4% of dividend changes were decreases.","marks":[]},{"data":{"ref":"828e1eb8-a240-4041-baae-1734044cf56f","stage":{"ref":"cbd78384-1318-46f6-8ce2-7c83238a5148","sections":[{"ref":"3ed070e4-3544-4c6a-91a6-c6f7643c005d","rows":[{"ref":"c4e3e0f5-58e3-4f68-b11f-88745a685fa6","columns":[{"ref":"91adc333-8b93-444a-8194-6cb391e0b384","stageElements":[{"ref":"deb5d01b-bb8e-40d0-b91b-b77fee3edd60","type":"stage-element-text","value":{"object":"value","document":{"object":"document","data":{},"nodes":[{"object":"block","type":"button","ref":"fef49aba-f758-4542-a612-5b288c914a97","nodes":[{"object":"block","type":"paragraph","ref":"ded20f7b-4edd-476b-84d4-322e951fbf3b","nodes":[{"object":"text","text":"F. Allen and R. Michaely, “Payout Policy,” in G. Constantinides, M. Harris, and R. Stulz, eds., ","marks":[]},{"object":"text","text":"Handbook of the Economics of Finance","marks":[{"type":"italic"}]},{"object":"text","text":" (2003).","marks":[]}],"data":{}}],"data":{}}]}}}]}]}]}]}},"nodes":[{"object":"text","text":"8","marks":[]}],"object":"inline","type":"footnote","ref":"092f6785-01b9-4ebe-9e50-ac967759bfb8"},{"object":"text","text":" In a classic survey of corporate executives, John Lintner suggested that these observations resulted from (1) management’s belief that investors prefer stable dividends with sustained growth and (2) management’s desire to maintain a long-term target level of dividends as a fraction of earnings.","marks":[]},{"data":{"ref":"b2169bda-d9b7-41f1-80c3-da28393483ea","stage":{"ref":"3abd7d9d-f67e-4cac-bd9a-4046c0a4fc79","sections":[{"ref":"c26ec7b4-9460-4c3d-bf94-55df81458444","rows":[{"ref":"bc68a96b-71c1-44db-a227-4a29acfd00b4","columns":[{"ref":"12011c39-aa20-4f2b-b881-6ad01a79b98d","stageElements":[{"ref":"5e7e33f1-ada9-4933-b800-3159a69e7f8d","type":"stage-element-text","value":{"object":"value","document":{"object":"document","data":{},"nodes":[{"object":"block","type":"button","ref":"b5c57133-ff0a-42c5-b8e3-57b736aa0cd6","nodes":[{"object":"block","type":"paragraph","ref":"250952e6-5f6e-4846-a845-c931df6d1cd2","nodes":[{"object":"text","text":"J. Lintner, “Distribution of Incomes of Corporations Among Dividends, Retained Earnings and Taxes,” ","marks":[]},{"object":"text","text":"American Economic Review","marks":[{"type":"italic"}]},{"object":"text","text":" 46 (1956): 97–113.","marks":[]}],"data":{}}],"data":{}}]}}}]}]}]}]}},"nodes":[{"object":"text","text":"9","marks":[]}],"object":"inline","type":"footnote","ref":"4551ea4f-bb6d-47cd-adfc-5848cd52b7c8"},{"object":"text","text":" Thus, firms raise their dividends only when they perceive a long-term sustainable increase in the expected level of future earnings, and cut them only as a last resort. While this is perhaps a good description of how firms ","marks":[]},{"object":"text","text":"do","marks":[{"type":"italic"}]},{"object":"text","text":" set their dividends, as we have shown in this chapter there is no clear reason why firms ","marks":[]},{"object":"text","text":"should","marks":[{"type":"italic"}]},{"object":"text","text":" smooth their dividends. One explanation is that it contributes to signaling with dividends, as discussed in the next section.","marks":[]}],"data":{}}]}},"config":{"cssClass":""},"ref":"91e415e5-336e-4853-aa93-bee3e72ec72f"}]}]},{"columns":[{"stageElements":[{"type":"stage-element-text","value":{"object":"value","document":{"object":"document","data":{},"nodes":[{"object":"block","type":"paragraph","ref":"4df6e80c-117d-4b65-9c5a-81adbb7d6fa3","nodes":[{"object":"text","text":"How can firms keep dividends smooth as earnings vary? As we have already discussed, firms can maintain almost any level of dividend in the short run by adjusting the number of shares they repurchase or issue and the amount of cash they retain. However, due to the tax and transaction costs of funding a dividend with new equity issues, managers do not wish to commit to a dividend that the firm cannot afford to pay out of regular earnings. For this reason, firms generally set dividends at a level they expect to be able to maintain based on the firm’s earnings prospects.","marks":[]}],"data":{}}]}},"config":{"cssClass":""},"ref":"20282c1e-298e-4d78-b320-8f57ba7664bc"}]}]}]}]},"screenType":"","transitions":{"enter":{"animation":"","duration":0,"easing":"","customKeyframes":""},"exit":{"animation":"","duration":0,"easing":"","customKeyframes":""}},"lockElements":false,"learnerCurrentAttempt":1,"footer":{"buttonText":"Next","buttonIcon":"Arrow","showFooter":false,"showHistoryNavButtons":false,"previewFooter":false,"position":"Fixed to screen bottom","footerComponent":{"showFooterDropArea":"hide","width":100,"footerComponentsAlignment":"right"}},"styles":{"background":{},"stage":{"maxWidth":940,"background":"rgba(255, 255, 255, 1)","responsive":true,"padding":{"vertical":60,"horizontal":60},"border":{"color":"rgba(224, 224, 224, 1)","radius":0,"width":0}},"elements":{"padding":{"vertical":10,"horizontal":10}},"footer":{"buttonColor":"rgba(0, 115, 202, 1)","textColor":"rgba(0, 0, 0, 0.7)","backgroundColor":"rgba(255, 255, 255, 1)","padding":10,"corners":4,"border":"none","shadow":"0 -1px 4px 0 rgba(0,0,0,0.06), 0 0 12px 2px rgba(0,0,0,0.1)"},"feedback":{"width":320,"textColor":"rgba(0, 0, 0, 0.7)","backgroundColor":"rgba(255, 255, 255, 1)","corners":4,"border":"none","shadow":"0 5px 47px 10px rgba(0,0,0,0.15), 0 10px 20px 2px rgba(0,0,0,0.1), 0 7px 8px 0 rgba(0,0,0,0.1)"}},"title":"Dividend Smoothing"},"assets":[{"urn":"urn:aero:cb03cb60-44e0-11ed-9967-59bbd5f34c83","asset":{"assetProvider":"ALFRESCO","id":"cb03cb60-44e0-11ed-9967-59bbd5f34c83","assetMediaType":"image","assetVisibility":"GLOBAL","ownerId":"e88133a0-8dc4-11eb-964e-4d7e264c9958","subscriptionId":"f0afd4d0-d2ff-11ea-9998-d57e1e28aca1","alfrescoId":"a3933c8e-166f-417c-957f-1f7a35673431","name":"FG_17_007.jpg","version":"2.0","lastModifiedDate":1664998397,"lastSyncDate":1665085928},"source":{"small":{"width":468,"url":"https://assets-bronte-qaint.pearson.com/cb03cb60-44e0-11ed-9967-59bbd5f34c83/small/4d702a036b1b5046ce4f56c8786cdc0c.jpeg","height":300},"original":{"width":937,"url":"https://assets-bronte-qaint.pearson.com/cb03cb60-44e0-11ed-9967-59bbd5f34c83/medium/4d702a036b1b5046ce4f56c8786cdc0c.jpeg","height":600},"medium":{"width":937,"url":"https://assets-bronte-qaint.pearson.com/cb03cb60-44e0-11ed-9967-59bbd5f34c83/medium/4d702a036b1b5046ce4f56c8786cdc0c.jpeg","height":600},"thumb":{"width":234,"url":"https://assets-bronte-qaint.pearson.com/cb03cb60-44e0-11ed-9967-59bbd5f34c83/thumb/4d702a036b1b5046ce4f56c8786cdc0c.jpeg","height":150}},"metadata":{"altText":"","workURN":"","caption":"<p>Compared to GM&#x2019;s earnings, its dividend payments were relatively stable until it finally suspended them in 2008 prior to filing for bankruptcy the next year. (Data adjusted for splits, earnings exclude extraordinary items.)</p>","alfrescoPath":"bronte-e2e-testing-qaint/documentLibrary/BV E2E Test/[10-05-2022] Berk","originalAssetName":"FG_17_007.jpg","longDesc":"","height":"513"}}],"scenarios":[],"pluginPayload":{"pluginRepositoryPath":"https://plugin-repository-bronte-qaint.pearson.com/9417ac60-5f60-11ea-8e69-affb2224d7e8/0.15.209/ac43ee4c0eda05e9718fa83a5aed4cff.zip","summary":{"pluginId":"9417ac60-5f60-11ea-8e69-affb2224d7e8","name":"Screen","description":"A screen of a lesson","type":"screen","latestVersion":"0.15.209","subscriptionId":"f0afd4d0-d2ff-11ea-9998-d57e1e28aca1","createdAt":"Fri, 6 Mar 2020 04:11:39 GMT","updatedAt":"Tue, 13 Dec 2022 22:07:46 GMT","tags":[],"publishMode":"DEFAULT"}},"activityThemeIconLibraries":[]}